# Architecture Rules

## Purpose
Ensure all code aligns with RE-OS modular monolith architecture, tenant isolation, and future microservice extraction seams documented in `docs/SYSTEM_DESIGN.md`.

## Requirements
- Organize backend as NestJS modules matching bounded contexts (auth, tenant, properties, crm, etc.).
- Use Controller → Service → Repository layering; no business logic in controllers.
- Every business DB query MUST scope by `tenant_id` from `TenantContext`.
- Emit domain events for cross-module side effects; use BullMQ for async work.
- Use UUID v7 for external IDs; never expose sequential IDs.
- Document architectural changes in `docs/SYSTEM_DESIGN.md` before implementation.

## Restrictions
- No direct cross-module repository imports — call public service interface or use events.
- No monolithic `utils.ts` for domain logic — belongs in module services.
- No shared mutable global state for tenant context.
- Do not introduce microservices until extraction criteria in SYSTEM_DESIGN are met.

## Best Practices
- Keep modules cohesive; shared code only in `common/` (guards, pipes, base repository).
- Design APIs versioned under `/api/v1`.
- Use outbox pattern preparation for future event bus migration.
- Feature flags for risky rollouts (Phase 9 table ready).

## Anti-Patterns
- God module importing everything.
- Fat controllers with validation + DB + email in one method.
- Bypassing tenant guard "just for admin scripts".
- Circular module dependencies.

## Examples

```typescript
// GOOD: Service enforces tenant + business rule
async updateInquiry(id: string, dto: UpdateInquiryDto, ctx: TenantContext) {
  const inquiry = await this.repo.findById(id, ctx.tenantId);
  if (!inquiry) throw new NotFoundException();
  this.pipelineService.validateTransition(inquiry.stageId, dto.stageId);
  return this.repo.update(id, dto, ctx);
}

// BAD: Controller queries DB directly
@Patch(':id')
update(@Param('id') id: string, @Body() body: any) {
  return this.prisma.inquiry.update({ where: { id }, data: body });
}
```
